By Pythagoras on right triangle $ABD,$
\[AB^2 = AD^2 + BD^2.\]By Pythagoras on right triangles $ACD$ and $BCD,$
\begin{align*}
AD^2 &= AC^2 - CD^2, \\
BD^2 &= BC^2 - CD^2,
\end{align*}so
\begin{align*}
\cos \angle ACB &= \frac{AC^2 + BC^2 - AB^2}{2 \cdot AC \cdot BC} \\
&= \frac{AC^2 + BC^2 - (AD^2 + BD^2)}{2 \cdot AC \cdot BC} \\
&= \frac{(AC^2 - AD^2) + (BC^2 - BD^2)}{2 \cdot AC \cdot BC} \\
&= \frac{2 \cdot CD^2}{2 \cdot AC \cdot BC} \\
&= \frac{CD}{AC} \cdot \frac{CD}{BC} \\
&= (\sin \angle CAD)(\sin \angle CBD) \\
&= \boxed{xy}.
\end{align*}

Let $O$ be the center of the sphere, and assume for now that $O$ is inside polyhedron $P$. We can carve polyhedron $P$ into pyramids, each of which has a face of $P$ as its base and $O$ as its apex. For example, a cube would be carved into six pyramids, two of which are highlighted in this drawing: [asy]
size(4cm);
import three;
triple A,B,C,D,EE,F,G,H;
